  "response": "It's difficult to definitively say who has been the \"most prolific\" Chief of Army Staff (COAS) as \"prolific\" can be interpreted in various ways. However, we can consider a few angles to address this:\n\n*   **Longest Tenure:**\n\n    *   **General Kodendera Subayya Thimayya** had one of the longest tenures as COAS, serving from May 1957 to May 1961. A long tenure allowed him more time to implement policies and reforms.\n\n*   **Impactful Contributions:**\n\n    *   **Field Marshal Sam Manekshaw:** He led the Indian Army to victory in the 1971 Indo-Pak war, resulting in the creation of Bangladesh. His leadership and strategic acumen were crucial, making him a highly influential and respected figure.\n    *   **General K. Sundarji:** He is credited with modernizing the Indian Army and introducing technological advancements. His reforms aimed to make the army more agile and effective.\n\n*   **Strategic Vision and Doctrines:**\n\n    *   Some COAS have been instrumental in shaping India's military doctrine and strategic thinking. Identifying a single \"most prolific\" in this aspect is subjective and depends on the specific doctrine or vision being considered.\n\n**Conclusion:**\n\nWhile General Thimayya had a long tenure, Field Marshal Sam Manekshaw is widely considered to be one of the most impactful COAS due to his leadership during the 1971 war. General Sundarji also made significant contributions to modernization. The \"most prolific\" depends on the criteria used, but these are three prominent figures to consider.",
